est that he was a gifted but complacent frequenter of courts, his attention dedicated to the wealthy and his sympathies to thepowerful, and moreover, that his poems pay the merest lipservice to religious observance. God and the Gawain-poet argues that, on the contrary, the poet's wide-ranging engagement with all human life explicitly acknowledgesall material creation as God's gift, revelling in its physicality, in bodily senses and movement and the ways a community celebrates itself. Dr Hatt shows how, in exhorting readers to recognize and respond to the narrative of divine gift, he appears as an energetic Christian poet and a humane and compassionate observer. Cecilia A. Hatt gained her D.Phil from Oxford University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArthurian romancesxHistory and criticism. 0aChristian poetry, English (Middle)xHistory and criticism. 0aChristianity and literature. 0aManuscripts, English (Middle)zEngland. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aArthurian Literature.  aCleanness.  aGawain-Poet.  aGenre.  aLiterary Analysis.  aLiterary Genres.  aLiterary Scholarship.  aMedieval Literature.  aMiddle English.  aPatience.  aPearl.  aSir Gawain.  aTheological Themes.  aTheology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311143132140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782045984?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782045984423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782045984/original  a978-3-11-143132-1  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles